<T1>a new york state supreme court judge granted a temporary restraining order against mandatory h1n1 flu vaccinations for healthcare workers.</T1>

<T1.1>the state health commissioner had issued a regulation requiring healthcare workers to be vaccinated.</T1.1>
<T1.1.1>workers were required to receive both seasonal and h1n1 flu vaccinations by november 30th.</T1.1.1>
<T1.1.2>those who refused vaccination would face disciplinary action.</T1.1.2>

<T1.2>the public employees federation filed a lawsuit challenging the mandate.</T1.2>
<T1.2.1>the federation is the second largest state employers union with 15,000 healthcare members.</T1.2.1>
<T1.2.2>approximately 5,000 members would be directly affected by the regulation.</T1.2.2>

<T1.3>judge thomas mcnamara granted the temporary restraining order on friday.</T1.3>
<T1.3.1>the order will remain in effect until the state supreme court reviews the case.</T1.3.1>
<T1.3.2>a hearing is scheduled for october 30th.</T1.3.2>

<T1.4>both sides presented arguments regarding the vaccination requirement.</T1.4>
<T1.4.1>federation president kenneth byrnien called the decision "a big step in the right direction."</T1.4.1>
<T1.4.2>council leader peter banks stated members oppose the mandate, not the vaccination program itself.</T1.4.2>
<T1.4.2.1>banks expressed concern about "putting conditions of service over an unproven vaccine."</T1.4.2.1>
<T1.4.2.2>he noted that a 1990 court ruling allowed philosophical or religious exemptions, which the new regulation lacks.</T1.4.2.2>
<T1.4.3>the state health department expressed confidence the regulation will be upheld.</T1.4.3>
<T1.4.3.1>officials cited a 1990 court ruling that rejected opposition to mandatory rubella vaccinations.</T1.4.3.1>
